segments.text: The individual holding both positions, of course, is obvious.
He has so much unlimited control.
The tie in between the two experiment stations is unusual in my mind for the president of the university.
there's almost an open playground upon which to switch here and there and there and here.
As you may recall, when I became chancellor, one of my
the board said to me, Hubert, we want to build a strong system.
You build it as strong as you can.
It wasn't because of that reason that I

recommended the change to them of separating out the Experiment Station and the Extension Service it was mainly because they were separate budget identities in the legislature and I didn't and they were as such I didn't think they should report through the Chief Executive Officer of another of another budget entity to get to where they're going too much opportunity to
to use the money freely and Very little accountability for the research programs How is research doing?
Are we earning our money?
Is this piece of research producing something and I know you can't Particularly in basic research.
You can't ask that question.
I

But in the applied research field, and much of ours was applied research, particularly in agriculture, to some extent in engineering, in applied research, it's easy to raise the question, how effective is it doing?
Are you fulfilling your role?
Is it quality material?
Those questions weren't being asked.
Back in the

rudder williams years can you think of any opportunities that a m missed are there some things in hindsight that we could have done yes very quickly i can come to a big one and that's the university of texas at arlington which at one time as you know was a part of the a m system

I think the relinquishing of that, almost voluntarily doing it, but in response, I think, to some protests from the Arlington people that they did not want to be associated with A&M, no one made an attempt, to my knowledge, to find out why and to correct it.
I never heard of anything either.
In fact, to my knowledge, nothing was done.
Now, I understood from the far sidelines that some of the regents were happy to, quote, get rid of it.
We can spend more money then on College Station.
Whatever the cause, it was short-sighted to have an opportunity to be a part of the Metroplex system, Dallas-Fort Worth system,
Wow.
Right.
Great opportunity.
Did you ever hear of any, during your day, of any other institutions in the state that might have come under the A&M system umbrella?
I heard talk at one time about Lamar.
I can't remember from which it came.
But the talk went along these lines.
It's an engineering-oriented type institution.
We would do well to have it as a part of this system, and it would give us a point of light in Southeast Texas.
But that was the only one I recall hearing about.
There was, I guess there was always some
talk about the Valley Schools, but not very explicit, nothing tangible.
Were there any, as you look back, are there any academic subject areas that Texas A&M University, you think, passed by that it might have added to the program here?
should we have tried to become completely comprehensive but i think time will take care of some of that uh... i think david maxwell's locating and bringing to this campus
The Nautical Archaeology Group was a great coup.
He brought that thing totally intact and put it in here.
I thought that was a sweeping success.
I remember when, because Winerdi and I were part of that effort when those people came.
Yeah, that was a great move for A&M.
And...
The Fine Arts program, of course, is one of continuing interest and I think, as I said, time will help with that.
I recall shortly after I became Dean of Liberal Arts, I had a visit from
two lady citizens of the College Station community who came to speak to me supporting further development in the fine arts.
And I was totally supportive, but at that time I said, ladies, at this time,
There is such a great pressure upon the resources of this university that I think there are other items, other areas which first must be sought and attained for us.
And I named philosophy, for example, as one of them.
And they agreed to that.
I think the coordinating, well, I think among our own reviewing points along the way, fine arts proposals would have had early on considerable difficulty.
And it's so costly.
Huh?
So costly for student credit hours.
Yes, yes.
Do you remember some people
that we miss some individuals that got away or that we almost attracted some key individuals anywhere through the years.
I remember a few early leavers
But they were at retirement age.
I'm thinking here of Clarence Zener, Horace Bowers.
They stayed such a short time, Haskell.
But we didn't lose them to someone else.
Yes.
They didn't stay here in the community.
No, no.
But I can't remember many people that were here.
and another school hired them away and all of us said oh look what they accomplished there.
What about looking now with a smile, do you remember some goofs, some flops, some failures by somewhere that you witnessed?
I'm sure there are some along the way.
All right, do you remember any proposals that you made at whatever level that you thought were important that were turned down?
Oh, gee.
Not here within the university, no.
Okay.
I can't think of anything.
I tried to, Haskell, I tried to pick, judiciously pick the things to carry forward that I thought were winners.
I've had people come to me from departments and from the faculty seeking this and that and that.

I would I'd say yes that that sounds like an important opportunity I said but I'm faced with I'm faced with a budget hearing next week and I don't want to our next month or whenever and I can't put that into the mix of things right now as Dr. Williams
became ill, do you remember your hearing of his illness, his heart attack?
In Houston?
Well, the night they flew him down there from here.
I didn't know of that, Haskell.
Oh, yes.
Claude Goswick was a young, new doctor at the health center, and I interviewed a young lady reporter
not so young anymore, for the battalion.
And she said that one of the emergency crew told her when they got to the president's house that Dr. Williams' heart wasn't beating.
I don't know this story at all.
And then they take him to Houston, and he has another heart attack.
And while DeBakey, do you remember how you heard about
Dr. Williams' illness?
No.
I don't recall that.
Were you aware beforehand, as you look back, were you aware that his strength was declining?
No.
I certainly wasn't.
No.
The interim president was Clyde Wells, wasn't it?
Clyde Wells served as interim president and chairman of the board.
What was that?
What a cushy condition.
What was that like for you key administrators on the campus?
I just ignored it.
Okay.
Because there were no important policy matters during that period, were there?
No.
All right, then the presidency is separated from the chancellorship.
and the board identifies a new president, did anybody consult with you as a dean for suggestion about a new president?
No.
What was the reaction of you and the other deans when Darvish was announced?
Uncertainty and surprise.
And then he selected Mac Prescott as his vice president.
Yes.
Did Mac change things much in his style from Dr. Calhoun?
I think to some extent, yes.
I was surprised that Mack as a vice president was, and as a scientist, biochemistry.
To me, scientists, when addressed by a problem, scope it out pretty thoroughly.
aspects of it.
I felt that Mack was more monolithic in his handling problems.
He would have, I don't want to say impulsive, but he would have
he would reach a decision and that decision might be based upon one facet of a multifaceted situation.
And I thought that was considerably different from Dr. Calhoun's style.
When Dr. Williams took the job in Houston,
A new chancellor of the system was identified.
What can you share with this machine about that process and how you were selected?
I really don't know exactly how my name came before the board.
I suspect to some extent that Bob Cherry may have at least placed my name, among others, before the board for consideration.
I was also told by Clyde Wells later on that Dr. Williams had given him two names in the event something happened to him.
One was John Calhoun, the other was Frank Hubert.
As far as you're aware, did they even consider Calhoun?
I don't know.
I've never heard, I don't know.
I think it was a Tuesday morning that they met.
I returned from East Texas State University where I had been consulting
The day before, got home, oh, 9 or 10 o'clock.
Mary Julia said, Frank, Mr. Clyde Wells has called from the board and invited you to have breakfast with him tomorrow morning.
I said, fine, okay.
I thought, I knew they were in a search, and I thought they were going to ask me
to give them some advice on search procedures.
I had consulted some with other institutions and with local school districts on such matters, and I thought maybe that was the basis for my being invited to breakfast with them.
Well, I went to breakfast.
Nice, congenial
After breakfast, Mr. Wells said, you're aware of the fact that we're in a search for a new chancellor, and we'd like to offer you the job.
Just bang like that.
Well, I was really caught by surprise, Haskell, startled.
I said, I have two questions.
First, have you discussed this with President Williams?
And they said no.
Wait, you said Williams.
Huh?
You said Williams.
President Miller.
President Miller, have you discussed this with President Miller?
And they said no, rather emphatically.
I next asked if they were aware that I would reach the age 65 the following summer and would be very likely retired.
They said, we're aware of that, but it's not a concern of ours.
And I recall Al Davies said, you can go to 70 as far as I'm concerned.
Now, this was what year?
This was 79.
This is September of 79, Haskell.
I said, when would you expect me to start?
And they said, tomorrow.
I said, well, I'm scheduled to leave tomorrow to go to the University of Georgia and make a speech over a two-day period to a group there in education.
And then I'll return.
I said, what would, I think October the 1st was the following Monday.
I said, how about that?
Okay.
So that took place.
I went back to the office, told Peggy, call Mary Julia first, and that's the way it happened.
It was a strange situation, Haskell, in a way.
And it was truly just completely a bolt out of the blue.
I had no idea, had not ever given it any consideration whatsoever.
And you're implying made not any effort.
No, none at all.
None whatsoever.
No phone calls, no third-party involvement.
aloof.
I wasn't a part of that.
I have the impression as an observer as dean of faculties then that fairly soon there were some disagreements between you and President Miller about where the stations and the services reported.
Is that correct?
Absolutely.
The board asked me to bring in a proposed organization plan for the system.
And I did this on my own, by myself, without consulting key staff in the chancellor's office, Freeman or Bond or Cherry or whomever.
I have a background to some extent in graduate studies in public administration.
I believed then as I believe today.
that a separate budget entity of the state of Texas should not report to its governing board through another budget entity.
I'm aware of the fact of the close relationship between University and Experiment Station.
But I'm also aware of the fact of a total lack of accountability, in my view, Haskell, of what's going on in the experiment station.
It's all one happy family, either in engineering or in agriculture.
That plus the fact that each of these entities
makes its own presentation to the legislature for its funding as a separate budget entity, sometimes with support from the president, but not always, not often.
So for the reason of direct reporting to your governing board,
and the accountability of your programs.
I felt that the service agencies, if they are to remain separate budget entities, should report to their governing board direct.
In other words, through the chancellor's office.
Jarvis and O.D.
Butler.
O.D., I think, had a pretty strong influence on Jarvis.
Jarvis and O.D.
vehemently opposed.
Don't fix it if it ain't broke.
I gave them my rationale.
And I told Jarvis, I said, I'm going to present this to the board.
had it all mapped out, and had, I thought, a cohesive coordinating group, which I called the Joint Committee on Agency and University Relationships, the JAGWR.

I, which was comprised of the president of the university as a presiding officer, the four directors of the experiment stations and extension services, the dean of, the vice president of the university, a couple of other representatives from the university, and from the chancellor's office, Clyde Freeman,
and James Bond.
I said this and I laid out the duties of that group there to meet monthly on matters relating to university agency relationships in three areas.
First, programs.
How shall the agencies support the programs of the university and vice versa?
And what shall the programs be?
What shall our effort be for the next biennium?
Personnel, staffing programs, and facilities.
Where shall they live?
And you guys make the recommendations to the chancellor's office, and I'll take them to the board with your strong support.
However, if any single one of you, I don't care who among you,
doesn't like the idea and doesn't accept it, you can veto it.
One person veto, in which case the matter comes to the chancellor direct and I'll make the decision.
God, I said, but the university president will chair this thing.
Jarvis never called a meeting.
Well, he didn't like the idea.
And I told him, when I took him a copy of it, I said, Jarvis, I'm going to take this to the board.
Between now and then, I do not want you to lobby any single member of the board.
You stay away from them.
You can make your own presentation to the board when you're ready, but I don't want you lobbying them beforehand.
He didn't do it, but he sent O.D.,
especially to agricultural-oriented people like the guy up at DeKalb, the banker at DeKalb, Texas, a forgotten little gray-headed fellow, nice guy, great guy.
And he raised questions about the reorganization.
I felt it was just too easy, you know, if a guy doesn't have a research project this year, we'll put him over here in teaching somewhere.
Teaching's got more money than it can use.
We'll put some research people on teaching money.
Incidentally, my second year in office at the chancellor's office, you might punch this off here.
This was then in this disagreement over organization and reporting authority was in late 79 and early 80.
I guess yes.
All right.
I remember coming to chat with you to say goodbye late in June of 1980.
One morning
before driving toward El Paso.
And you asked me about who the best deans were, I mean best department heads were on the campus.
And you particularly singled out engineering and then you asked me about Chuck Sampson.
And I gave you a very vague answer because at that point he was no longer a department head.
And then I learned two days later that Dr. Miller,
had been terminated.
Can you share any information about how that decision came to be made?
Yes.
Let me go back a ways before that.
For what purposes or what reasons I do not know.
Where are we?
That the board apparently had reached a decision that they thought a chain was in order.
Is that correct?
Yes.
That was clear.
And I talked to the president about it, advised him of it.
I had a visit from O.D.
Butler saying, Frank, you've got to protect the president.
